{"name": "etl-db-tools", "metadata": {"name": "etl-db-tools", "version": "0.1.1a0", "classifiers": ["Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.13"], "home_page": null, "license": null, "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": ["pyodbc", "tomli", "jinja2"], "summary": null, "upload_time": 1733780671}, "documentation": ["# Etl-db-Tools\n\nThis package provides some convenience functions for interacting with databases. For instance executing queries, copying a table etc. It uses pyodbc as a the backend. \n\n### install\n```\npip install etl-db-tools\n```\n\n## Getting started\n\n#### Set up a connection with a sql server database\n\n``` python\nfrom etl_db_tools.sqlservertools import sqlservertools as sql\n\ncnxn = sql.SQLserverconnection(driver='ODBC Driver 18 for SQL Server', \n                            server='localhost_or_else', \n                            database='TestDB', \n                            uid = 'your_username',\n                            pwd = 'your_password', \n                            TrustServerCertificate = 'yes')\n\n```\n#### Select data from an active connection\nYou can use the connect method as a context manager.\n\n``` python\n# create an active connection as context manager\nwith cnxn.connect() as active_cnxn:\n    query = \"\"\"select id, name from dbo.myTable \"\"\"\n    data = cnxn.select_data(query)\n```\n\nSelect_data() yields a generator. This will return list of dictionaries containing the query results.\n\n#### use the data\n\n``` python\nfor row in data:\n    print(f\"id = {row['id']}\")\n```\n\n"], "modules": [{"name": "etl_db_tools.sqlservertools.sqlservertools", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "etl_db_tools.sqlservertools.sqlservertools.copy_table", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "source_connection", "type": {"name": "Connection", "xref": {"fqname": "etl_db_tools.base.connection.Connection", "project": null}, "params": null}, "default": null}, {"name": "table_n